-- в”Ђв”Ђ Krayin CRM в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Free, open-source, Laravel-based CRM for lead, deal and customer lifecycle management, built by the team behind Bagisto.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2021, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Noida, India$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Krayin CRM Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Krayin CRM is a free, open-source Laravel CRM for lead and deal management. See its features, premium extensions and how it compares to SuiteCRM and Odoo.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Krayin CRM is an open-source customer relationship management platform launched in 2021 by Jitendra Singh, Saurav Pathak and Vipin Sahu, and developed by Webkul Software, an established Indian IT product company founded in 2010 and headquartered in Noida, Uttar Pradesh, India, with roughly 550 employees spread across Asia, North America and Africa as of 2026. Webkul is also the company behind Bagisto, a well-known open-source Laravel-based e-commerce platform, and Krayin CRM was built by the same engineering team using the same core technology stack, applying Bagisto's open-source, self-hosted philosophy to the CRM category. Architecturally, Krayin is built entirely on Laravel, the popular PHP web application framework, with Vue.js powering its frontend interface, making it a fully self-hostable application that businesses can deploy on their own servers or a cloud provider of choice rather than relying on a vendor-hosted SaaS instance, and giving developers already familiar with the Laravel ecosystem a natural path to customize or extend the CRM's codebase. The product covers the core functional areas expected of a modern CRM: lead capture and tracking, a visual deal pipeline for managing sales opportunities through configurable stages, sales forecasting, and tools for campaign management, email marketing and customer segmentation that let sales and marketing teams target specific groups of contacts with tailored messaging. Krayin also bundles functionality that many competing CRMs вЂ” including some commercial ones вЂ” reserve for paid tiers, such as a built-in product catalog and a quoting module for generating and sending sales quotes directly from the CRM, along with omnichannel customer engagement tools spanning VoIP calling, live chat and structured customer feedback collection. More recently, Krayin has begun incorporating AI-powered automation into its workflow engine, including AI-driven lead scoring to help sales teams prioritize the most promising opportunities, automated support-ticket classification, customer intent prediction, and an AI chatbot for handling routine inbound queries, extending the platform's original sales-pipeline focus into broader AI-assisted customer lifecycle management. Krayin's licensing model is entirely free: the core CRM is released under the MIT License, meaning businesses can download, self-host, modify and deploy it commercially without paying any licensing fee, and Webkul has publicly committed to keeping the core open-source framework free permanently. Revenue for Webkul instead comes from optional premium extensions sold through its online store on a one-time-purchase basis rather than a recurring subscription вЂ” for example, a WhatsApp integration extension is priced at $1,499 and a VoIP calling extension at $4,500 вЂ” as well as from paid implementation, customization and support services for businesses that want professional help deploying or extending Krayin, and from a multi-tenant SaaS module that lets agencies or larger businesses run Krayin as a hosted, white-labeled CRM product for their own customers. Krayin's target audience is primarily small and medium-sized enterprises, as well as developers and digital agencies, that want full ownership and control over their CRM data and infrastructure without paying per-user SaaS subscription fees, and that are comfortable with or actively prefer a self-hosted, Laravel-based technology stack that they can customize beyond what a closed commercial CRM would allow. Within the open-source CRM category, Krayin's most direct competitors are SuiteCRM and EspoCRM, both long-established, free, self-hostable CRM platforms with large plugin ecosystems, and Odoo's CRM module, which is open source at its core but typically sold as part of Odoo's broader paid business-suite subscription; among commercial SaaS CRMs, Krayin competes indirectly with Salesforce, HubSpot CRM, Zoho CRM and Vtiger for budget-conscious teams evaluating whether to self-host versus subscribe. Krayin differentiates itself primarily through its modern Laravel and Vue.js technology stack (which many PHP developers find more approachable and contemporary than the older codebases underlying SuiteCRM or EspoCRM), its MIT-licensed permanently free core, its inclusion of quoting and product-catalog functionality that other open-source CRMs often lack out of the box, and its backing by Webkul, an already-profitable, multi-product software company with an established track record supporting Bagisto, which gives Krayin a level of ongoing development and commercial support infrastructure that many purely community-driven open-source CRM projects do not have.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'a346f9ff-ee8c-46ac-9a67-521ae858c58b';

